t also the dense entanglements among those in the top echelon of the party. Wang discusses the causes for failure of China’s socialist revolution and raises fundamental questions about male dominance in social movements that aim to pursue social justice and equality. This is the first book engendering the PRC high politics and has important theoretical and methodological implications for scholars and students working in gender studies as well as China studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aFeminismxPolitical aspectszChinaxHistory. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszChinaxHistory. 0aSocialism and motion pictureszChinaxHistoryy1949-1976. 0aSocialism and motion pictureszChinaxHistory. 0aWomenzChinaxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aacademic.  accp.  achina.  achinese communist party.  achinese culture.  achinese feminist.  achinese film.  achinese.  acinema.  aclass equality.  aclassism.  aclassist.  aculture.  aequality.  afemale issues.  afeminism in china.  afeminism.  afeminist film.  afeminist history.  afeminist.  afilm industry.  afilm.  agender equality.  ahidden history.  ainternational.  ajustice.  anew culture.  apatriarchy.  arevolution.  ascholarly.  asexism.  asocialist.  auntold stories.  awomens issues.  awomens rights.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052029228440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965867?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965867423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965867/original  a978-3-11-066754-7